<subSubSection id="C35F655AFFC8FFDCFF65F976B4F19DB6" pageId="3" pageNumber="441" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFA36D1FFC8FFDCFF65F976B4F19DB6" blockId="3.[151,1437,1244,1846]" pageId="3" pageNumber="441">
<emphasis id="B931EAC3FFC8FFDCFF65F976B51F9DFE" bold="true" box="[199,315,1676,1702]" pageId="3" pageNumber="441">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species can be distinguished from other species in this genus by the style apex resembling a sickle in lateral view, the pre-atrial process surpassing the aedeagal shaft and the absence of processes on aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35F655AFFC8FFDCFF65F902B5D29C6E" pageId="3" pageNumber="441" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BFA36D1FFC8FFDCFF65F902B5D29C6E" blockId="3.[151,1437,1244,1846]" pageId="3" pageNumber="441">
<emphasis id="B931EAC3FFC8FFDCFF65F902B56A9C4A" bold="true" box="[199,334,1784,1810]" pageId="3" pageNumber="441">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin “drepanoides”, referring to the style apex resembling a sickle or hook in lateral view.
</paragraph>
